messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Analysis results for the endpoint implemented by PrintRequestController#printDocument

- Full HTTP request path: /printdocument
  - There are no path parameters for this endpoint, so no curly brace placeholders are needed.

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable for this endpoint? No.
  - The method is explicitly restricted to POST via @RequestMapping(value = "/printdocument", method = RequestMethod.POST). Other methods are not mapped for this path.

- HEAD: Not acceptable
  - There is no handler method for HEAD on /printdocument. Since only POST is mapped, HEAD is not supported by this endpoint.

- POST: Acceptable
  - Yes. The endpoint is defined with method = RequestMethod.POST.

- OPTIONS: Acceptable
  - Yes. Spring will respond to OPTIONS for this mapped path, listing allowed methods (POST). This is consistent with the existing POST mapping.

- TRACE: Not acceptable
  - No TRACE mapping is defined for this path, so TRACE is not supported.

- GET: Not acceptable
  - No GET mapping for /printdocument is defined in this controller for this path.

- PUT: Not acceptable
  - No PUT mapping for this path.

- DELETE: Not acceptable
  - No DELETE mapping for this path.

- PATCH: Not acceptable
  - No PATCH mapping for this path.

Explanation:
- The printDocument method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printdocument", method = RequestMethod.POST), which means only HTTP POST requests to /printdocument are handled by this endpoint.
- Spring can automatically handle OPTIONS for a mapped path by exposing the allowed methods (in this case, POST). All other methods (HEAD, GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, TRACE) are not mapped to this path and are therefore not acceptable for this endpoint.
